{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492282","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492282"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:24:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:24:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1029"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1029","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1029"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.75,0.07,0.03,0.06,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1029"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92813"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1029","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1029"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1029"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76172"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"191"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"8753"},{"type":"tags","id":"9190"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5266"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6376"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30944"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38632"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92813","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/92813"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 67-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a one-week history of post-prandial vomiting. The vomiting occurs immediately after she has eaten. She had a Roux-en-Y gastric bypass (RYGB) surgery for morbid obesity four weeks earlier. She has made an uneventful recovery from the procedure and her current symptoms started soon after she got back on to her normal diet. She has lost 10 kg since the operation. She has a medical history of hypertension and type 2 diabetes. Her medications include metformin, amlodipine, and pantoprazole. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 130/90 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. Abdominal examination reveals a soft abdomen with well-healed surgical scars. The rest of the physical examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Over-eating","Anastomotic leak","Anastomotic ulcer","Internal hernia","Small bowel obstruction"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with immediate post-prandial vomiting four weeks after Roux-en-Y gastric bypass surgery. The absence of abdominal pain, tenderness, or systemic symptoms makes a serious complication less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOver-eating\u003C/strong\u003E is a common issue post-gastric bypass surgery, and is most likely in this case due to the absence of systemic effects and a normal abdominal examination. This occurs as the patient adapts to having a smaller gastric pouch with less capacity for food. Patients are advised to eat multiple small meals throughout the day and ensure food and drinks are spaced apart. This issue typically resolves as patients gain a better sense of tolerable portion size.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnastomotic leak\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with abdominal pain, tenderness, an acute abdomen and septic vitals (tachycardia, fever, respiratory distress). Investigation may include gastrografin study or CT abdomen. This patient does not present with signs concerning for an anastomotic leak.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnastomotic ulcer, \u003C/strong\u003Eor marginal ulcer, are typically a late complication of RYGB, though they could occur as early as four weeks post-operatively. These typically presents with nausea, epigastric pain, and GI bleeding. Risk factors include smoking, \u003Cem\u003EH. pylori\u003C/em\u003E infection, and NSAID use. Diagnosis is confirmed with upper endoscopy. Our patient\u0027s presentation is not suggestive of an anastomotic ulcer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInternal hernia\u003C/strong\u003E can occur at any time post-op. Pain is typically epigastric and may radiate to the back. If undetected, this could result in bowel ischaemia. Investigation includes gastrografin study or CT abdomen, though exploratory surgery may be needed for definitive diagnosis. Our patient lacks the characteristic pain pattern.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESmall bowel obstruction\u003C/strong\u003E can occur at any time post-RYGB due to adhesions, strictures, or hernias. While vomiting would be expected, crampy periumbilical pain and abdominal distension would also typically be present, which are absent in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Post-gastric bypass patients should be educated about appropriate portion sizes to prevent over-eating and subsequent vomiting.","Immediate post-prandial vomiting without abdominal pain or systemic symptoms in a post-gastric bypass patient is most likely due to over-eating.","Serious complications of gastric bypass surgery such as anastomotic leak, internal hernia, or obstruction typically present with abdominal pain, tenderness, or systemic symptoms."],"references":["Mechanick JI, Kushner RF, Sugerman HJ, Gonzalez-Campoy JM, Collazo-Clavell ML, Spitz AF, et al. American Association of Clinical Endocrinologists, The Obesity Society, and American Society for Metabolic \u0026 Bariatric Surgery medical guidelines for clinical practice for the perioperative nutritional, metabolic, and nonsurgical support of the bariatric surgery patient. Obesity (Silver Spring). 2009;17 Suppl 1:S1-70. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/19319140/","Stanford, FC. Bariatric surgery sequelae. In: BMJ Best Practice [online]. 2018; cited 2022 May 23. Available at: https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/1046."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76172"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1029"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76172","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/76172"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-19T14:06:31+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-19T14:08:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1029"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92813"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"d